[1
Date: Mon, 17 Jul 2000 09:14:40 +0200
From: Debora MacKenzie <d.mackenzie@chello.be>

Birds and the transmission of West Nile virus
The moderator asked, regarding Eleanor Kellon's query about bird deaths and
the spread of West Nile virus in North America, whether "statistics are
available from the dynamics of bird death during 1999 outbreak to allow
some provisional prediction". There is an analysis, published recently in
Emerging Infectious Diseases (at
http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/eid/vol6no4/rappole.htm), tracing the paths of
migratory birds known to acquire the virus, which clustered in large
numbers on wetlands with mosquitoes that can spread the virus near New York
during their migrations last autumn. The conclusion was that the virus
could have spread throughout North America, and to Central America,
northern South America and the Caribbean by now.
The question for human risk is whether the virus has actually been carried
to any region by enough birds, with enough viremia, that were then exposed
to enough mosquitoes to establish a local chain of transmission among
potential local carrier birds. Several species, such as eastern phoebes,
have been found carrying West Nile virus asymptomatically despite high
levels of viremia, meaning it could have travelled in migrants and will
circulate locally if enough local birds are infected, without necessarily
causing a visible surge in dead birds. Dead birds are in any case not
always terribly visible.
European researchers familiar with the virus in its home territory say
human outbreaks occur when prevalence in urban birds is high. This was the
case in New York at the time of the human outbreak last year. The authors
of the EID paper predicted that the Gulf Coast of the US was the next most
likely site for a human outbreak in North America, as the northern migrants
that go there remain more concentrated than migrants elsewhere and could
have transmitted the virus most frequently to local birds. But the question
can only be answered by looking for the virus in local, healthy, wild
birds. Here there appears to be a difference of opinion between veterinary
and medical authorities. The US monitoring programme is focused on testing
dead birds, sentinel chickens, mosquitoes, horses and humans. US veterinary
experts want to test healthy wild birds, preferably this autumn after they
have been exposed to a season of potentially infected mosquitoes and any
infection will be maximally detectable. This study had not, as of a week
ago, yet been funded.
Yet veterinary experts warn that testing dead birds and chickens lacks
sensitivity, and may not detect the next focus of enzooticity. Medical
authorities, on the other hand, fear testing wild birds may not be
cost-effective. Yet around ten state authorities do so regularly to keep an
eye on the related, native virus that causes St. Louis encephalitis.
Unfortunately these states are in areas, chiefly the Midwest, where the
last St. Louis outbreak occurred, not where the migratory birds' pathways
suggest West Nile may next migrate.
A journalistic report of the situation may be read at:
<http://www.newscientist.com/news/news_224631.html>.
Related editorial comment on the way in which West Nile virus has pointed
up the need for better communication between MDs and DVMs (a point made
often on ProMED-mail!) is at:
<http://www.newscientist.com/editorial/editorial.jsp?id=ns224648>.
--
Debora MacKenzie,
Europe correspondent,
New Scientist
<d.mackenzie@chello.be>
