[3
Date:Sun, 16 Jul 2000 01:10:50 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Newsday, 15 Jul 2000 [edited

Virus Found in 3rd Suffolk County Crow; bird count up-date
A third crow in Suffolk County has tested positive for West Nile virus,
health officials announced Friday. The crow, found in a residential area of
Wading River, was young. Since the bird was not born last year, this might
indicate that the bird had been infected this year by [virus-infected
mosquitoes, according to Health Commissioner Clare Bradley. Last Friday,
Bradley announced that two adult crows found in Lindenhurst and West
Babylon had tested positive for the virus, but said it was unclear whether
they had become infected this year or last year.
However, this young crow did not test positive on all tests, making it
difficult to say definitively that the bird had been bitten this year,
Bradley said. "We can't say with 100 percent certainty that this is current
infection. The fact that it is a fledgling indicates it might be, but it's
possible that it was somehow otherwise exposed -- it could have been
infected at birth [by the mother... We just don't know that much about
this virus," Bradley said.
Bradley added that there are no plans to spray the area because mosquito
counts remain low. "The benefit is just not there for me [!... It would be
like shooting a rabbit with a bazooka," Bradley said. However, she
cautioned people to avoid going into areas where they know there are lots
of mosquitoes. Bradley said the crow, which was picked up June 6 -- the
same day the two previous positive Suffolk crows were picked up -- tested
positive by two tests, by [a standard polymerase chain reaction test, and
by a more sophisticated Pachman [? PCR test. But it tested negative by an
immunofluorescent antibody test and did not culture, meaning that
scientists were unable to grow the virus in the lab.
The State Health Department announced on Wednesday that a red-tailed hawk
in Westchester County had tested positive, bringing to two the number of
positive birds in that county this year. Three more dead crows -- making a
total of 7 -- have tested positive in Bergen County, N.J., authorities said
on Friday. Also 4 crows and a blue jay have tested positive this year in
Rockland. To date, no crows have tested positive in Nassau County or New
York City, the epicenter of last year's outbreak. Bradley said scientists
from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention this week visited
Babylon, where the two previous positive crows were found. On Monday, the
U.S. Geological Survey and CDC will test roosting birds near where the
virus-positive crows had been found previously.

[Byline: Ridgelay Ochs
