Date: Sun, 16 Jul 2000 19:33:03 -0400
From: Dr. Laura D. Kramer, Arbovirus Lab., Wadsworth Center, NYS Department
of Health
<ldk02@health.state.ny.us>

Statement on test procedures from the Arbovirus Laboratory of the Wadsworth
Center (New York State Department of Health)
Tissues from dead birds submitted to the Wadsworth Laboratory for detection
of West Nile virus (WNV)are tested by procedures to detect viral RNA, viral
antigen, and infectious virus. To detect RNA, two sets of primers are used
in two separate TaqMan assays. If positive, two additional sets of primers
are used in two standard RT-PCR assays using newly excised tissue. A bird
is considered positive if these 4 assays are positive.
To detect viral antigen, frozen tissue sections are stained with monoclonal
antibody to WNV. If this assay is positive, or virus is detected by plaque
assay and/or evidence of cytopathology in Vero cell culture (followed by
IFA staining with monoclonal antibody to WNV), the bird is confirmed
positive. Sometimes the bird is submitted with the tissues badly autolyzed
and no virus is isolated; at other times, most commonly with blue jays, the
virus appears to be present at low levels and virus is not isolated. In
these situations, we continue to try to isolate virus by further passage in
Vero cell culture, and try other tissues and other cell cultures such as
C636. Positive results by cell culture or IFA on frozen sections is the
additional confirmation we seek.
--
Dr. Laura D. Kramer, Director
Arbovirus Lab - Wadsworth Center
New York State Department of Health
<ldk02@health.state.ny.us>
